    <title>Combined summary - Chain pruning</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T19:39:22.594490+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-April/005199.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin network is facing scalability issues due to the ever-increasing size of the blockchain. The discussions on the Bitcoin-development mailing list revolve around finding ways to address these issues. One suggestion is to form "superblocks" that can be pieced together from different nodes to serve as full portions of the blockchain for participants with limited resources. However, it is acknowledged that the main problem with compressing the blockchain is that it mostly consists of random bytes which do not compress well enough to change the fundamental physics.Another topic discussed is the use of merkle UTXO commitments to shape the UTXO set as a merkle tree and compute its root after every block. This enables a full node to copy the chain state from someone else and check that its hash matches what the block chain commits to. Combining this with "superblocks" that summarize past blocks could potentially allow participants with limited resources to serve full portions of the blockchain. However, there are differing opinions on whether this method is strictly more secure than SPV or a reduction in security.There are also concerns raised about using hashrate alone to determine the validity of UTXO sets, as it can lead to accepting an invalid version of history in the event of a 51% attack. Invalidation proofs could help address this issue. Other topics included the removal of checkpoints, compression of the blockchain, and the possibility of forming fixed ranges of blocks that nodes store and serve.Efforts to improve the efficiency and scalability of blockchain technology are ongoing. Suggestions for improving storage efficiency and reducing network activity include compressing and storing transaction sets as archive sets, and serving up these sets conditionally based on a rotational request period. The conversation demonstrates ongoing efforts to address the scalability issues faced by the Bitcoin network due to the ever-increasing size of the blockchain.In terms of security, relying on the longest chain (with the most proof of work) to commit to a valid UTXO set is seen as a reduction in security. Checkpoints are currently being used to guarantee that a longer chain starting before the checkpoint will not be accepted suddenly. Pieter Wuille suggests storing only unspent wallets before the last checkpoint and verifying "unspent wallet accounting" using only that checkpoint data, which the merkle tree can do.Finally, there are suggestions for improving the storage of the blockchain, such as storing it on tape and spooling it off at high speed using direct DMA from tape drive to NIC. The discussions demonstrate the ongoing evolution of Bitcoin's security measures and potential for greater efficiency in blockchain storage and verification.</summary>
